HEADWORD: Junto
<hw>Jun"to</hw> <pr>(j⟦ucr⟧n"t⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Juntos</plw> <pr>(j⟦ucr⟧n"t⟦osl⟧s)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[Sp. <ets>junto</ets> united. See <er>Junta</er>.]</ety> <def>A
secret council to deliberate on affairs of government or politics; a
number of men combined for party intrigue; a faction; a cabal; <as>as, a
<ex>junto</ex> of ministers; a <ex>junto</ex> of
politicians.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The puzzling sons of party next appeared,⟦br⟧
In dark cabals and mighty <qex>juntos</qex> met.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jupartie</ent>⟦br⟧
